     1	LS(1)                                  User Commands                                 LS(1)
     2	
     3	NAME
     4	       ls - list directory contents
     5	
     6	SYNOPSIS
     7	       ls [OPTION]... [FILE]...
     8	
     9	DESCRIPTION
    10	       List  information about the FILEs (the current directory by default).  Sort entries
    11	       alphabetically if none of -cftuvSUX nor --sort is specified.
    12	
    13	       Mandatory arguments to long options are mandatory for short options too.
    14	
    15	       -a, --all
    16	              do not ignore entries starting with .
    17	
    18	       -A, --almost-all
    19	              do not list implied . and ..
    20	
    21	       --author
    22	              with -l, print the author of each file
    23	
    24	       -b, --escape
    25	              print C-style escapes for nongraphic characters
    26	
    27	       --block-size=SIZE
    28	              scale sizes by SIZE before  printing  them;  e.g.,  '--block-size=M'  prints
    29	              sizes in units of 1,048,576 bytes; see SIZE format below
    30	
    31	       -B, --ignore-backups
    32	              do not list implied entries ending with ~
    33	
    34	       -c     with -lt: sort by, and show, ctime (time of last modification of file status
    35	              information); with -l: show ctime and  sort  by  name;  otherwise:  sort  by
    36	              ctime, newest first
    37	
    38	       -C     list entries by columns
    39	
    40	       --color[=WHEN]
    41	              colorize  the  output; WHEN can be 'always' (default if omitted), 'auto', or
    42	              'never'; more info below
    43	
    44	       -d, --directory
    45	              list directories themselves, not their contents
    46	
    47	       -D, --dired
    48	              generate output designed for Emacs' dired mode
    49	
    50	       -f     do not sort, enable -aU, disable -ls --color
    51	
    52	       -F, --classify
    53	              append indicator (one of */=>@|) to entries
    54	
    55	       --file-type
    56	              likewise, except do not append '*'
    57	
    58	       --format=WORD
    59	              across -x, commas -m, horizontal -x, long -l, single-column -1, verbose  -l,
    60	              vertical -C
    61	
    62	       --full-time
    63	              like -l --time-style=full-iso
    64	
    65	       -g     like -l, but do not list owner
    66	
    67	       --group-directories-first
    68	              group directories before files;
    69	
    70	              can  be augmented with a --sort option, but any use of --sort=none (-U) dis‐
    71	              ables grouping
    72	
    73	       -G, --no-group
    74	              in a long listing, don't print group names
    75	
    76	       -h, --human-readable
    77	              with -l and/or -s, print human readable sizes (e.g., 1K 234M 2G)
    78	
    79	       --si   likewise, but use powers of 1000 not 1024
    80	
    81	       -H, --dereference-command-line
    82	              follow symbolic links listed on the command line
    83	
    84	       --dereference-command-line-symlink-to-dir
    85	              follow each command line symbolic link
    86	
    87	              that points to a directory
    88	
    89	       --hide=PATTERN
    90	              do not list implied entries matching shell PATTERN (overridden by -a or -A)
    91	
    92	       --hyperlink[=WHEN]
    93	              hyperlink file names; WHEN can be 'always' (default if omitted), 'auto',  or
    94	              'never'
    95	
    96	       --indicator-style=WORD
    97	              append indicator with style WORD to entry names: none (default), slash (-p),
    98	              file-type (--file-type), classify (-F)
    99	
   100	       -i, --inode
   101	              print the index number of each file
   102	
   103	       -I, --ignore=PATTERN
   104	              do not list implied entries matching shell PATTERN
   105	
   106	       -k, --kibibytes
   107	              default to 1024-byte blocks for disk usage
   108	
   109	       -l     use a long listing format
   110	
   111	       -L, --dereference
   112	              when showing file information for a symbolic link, show information for  the
   113	              file the link references rather than for the link itself
   114	
   115	       -m     fill width with a comma separated list of entries
   116	
   117	       -n, --numeric-uid-gid
   118	              like -l, but list numeric user and group IDs
   119	
   120	       -N, --literal
   121	              print entry names without quoting
   122	
   123	       -o     like -l, but do not list group information
   124	
   125	       -p, --indicator-style=slash
   126	              append / indicator to directories
   127	
   128	       -q, --hide-control-chars
   129	              print ? instead of nongraphic characters
   130	
   131	       --show-control-chars
   132	              show  nongraphic  characters  as-is (the default, unless program is 'ls' and
   133	              output is a terminal)
   134	
   135	       -Q, --quote-name
   136	              enclose entry names in double quotes
   137	
   138	       --quoting-style=WORD
   139	              use  quoting  style  WORD  for  entry   names:   literal,   locale,   shell,
   140	              shell-always, shell-escape, shell-escape-always, c, escape
   141	
   142	       -r, --reverse
   143	              reverse order while sorting
   144	
   145	       -R, --recursive
   146	              list subdirectories recursively
   147	
   148	       -s, --size
   149	              print the allocated size of each file, in blocks
   150	
   151	       -S     sort by file size, largest first
   152	
   153	       --sort=WORD
   154	              sort by WORD instead of name: none (-U), size (-S), time (-t), version (-v),
   155	              extension (-X)
   156	
   157	       --time=WORD
   158	              with -l, show time as WORD instead of default modification  time:  atime  or
   159	              access  or  use  (-u); ctime or status (-c); also use specified time as sort
   160	              key if --sort=time (newest first)
   161	
   162	       --time-style=STYLE
   163	              with -l, show times using style STYLE: full-iso, long-iso, iso,  locale,  or
   164	              +FORMAT;  FORMAT  is  interpreted  like in 'date'; if FORMAT is FORMAT1<new‐
   165	              line>FORMAT2, then FORMAT1 applies to non-recent files and FORMAT2 to recent
   166	              files;  if  STYLE is prefixed with 'posix-', STYLE takes effect only outside
   167	              the POSIX locale
   168	
   169	       -t     sort by modification time, newest first
   170	
   171	       -T, --tabsize=COLS
   172	              assume tab stops at each COLS instead of 8
   173	
   174	       -u     with -lt: sort by, and show, access time; with -l: show access time and sort
   175	              by name; otherwise: sort by access time, newest first
   176	
   177	       -U     do not sort; list entries in directory order
   178	
   179	       -v     natural sort of (version) numbers within text
   180	
   181	       -w, --width=COLS
   182	              set output width to COLS.  0 means no limit
   183	
   184	       -x     list entries by lines instead of by columns
   185	
   186	       -X     sort alphabetically by entry extension
   187	
   188	       -Z, --context
   189	              print any security context of each file
   190	
   191	       -1     list one file per line.  Avoid '\n' with -q or -b
   192	
   193	       --help display this help and exit
   194	
   195	       --version
   196	              output version information and exit
   197	
   198	       The SIZE argument is an integer and optional unit (example: 10K is 10*1024).  Units
   199	       are K,M,G,T,P,E,Z,Y (powers of 1024) or KB,MB,... (powers of 1000).
   200	
   201	       Using color to distinguish  file  types  is  disabled  both  by  default  and  with
   202	       --color=never.   With  --color=auto, ls emits color codes only when standard output
   203	       is connected to a terminal.  The LS_COLORS environment variable can change the set‐
   204	       tings.  Use the dircolors command to set it.
   205	
   206	   Exit status:
   207	       0      if OK,
   208	
   209	       1      if minor problems (e.g., cannot access subdirectory),
   210	
   211	       2      if serious trouble (e.g., cannot access command-line argument).
   212	
